WEBVTT

00:01.669 --> 00:05.137
Narrator: This time on
"impossible engineering,"

00:05.139 --> 00:08.574
The highest railway
ever built...

00:08.576 --> 00:11.143
The engineering is mind-blowing.

00:11.145 --> 00:12.811
It was almost impossible

00:12.813 --> 00:16.115
To conceive of a railway
running at this altitude.

00:16.117 --> 00:19.585
Narrator: ...Constructed in
a remote, frozen wilderness...

00:19.587 --> 00:20.986
It's definitely amazing.

00:20.988 --> 00:22.821
It's a totally
different setting.

00:22.823 --> 00:25.657
...And the pioneering,
historic innovations...

00:25.659 --> 00:27.326
[ high-pitched ]
we're at 30 meters.

00:27.328 --> 00:28.994
One of the biggest changes
is my voice.

00:28.996 --> 00:31.463
I speak in
a very strange manner.

00:31.465 --> 00:34.533
Dickrell: I can sense the lack
of oxygen through my lungs.

00:34.535 --> 00:37.669
Lightheaded. Do not feel great.

00:37.671 --> 00:42.041
Narrator: ...That made
the impossible possible.

00:42.043 --> 00:45.411
-- Captions by vitac --
 www.Vitac.Com

00:45.413 --> 00:49.314
Captions paid for by
discovery communications

00:49.316 --> 00:51.550
This is lhasa,

00:51.552 --> 00:54.987
The spiritual home
of tibetan buddhism.

00:54.989 --> 00:57.356
This city in the clouds
is one of the highest,

00:57.358 --> 01:00.859
Most inaccessible on earth.

01:00.861 --> 01:04.430
Situated on the vast
tibetan plateau,

01:04.432 --> 01:06.632
It is surrounded by not one

01:06.634 --> 01:09.401
But three
mighty mountain ranges.

01:09.403 --> 01:12.571
♪

01:12.573 --> 01:14.773
Before the 1950s,
there weren't even any roads

01:14.775 --> 01:17.743
To get to lhasa --
just meandering mountain paths

01:17.745 --> 01:21.346
That took months to get through,
and only in good weather.

01:21.348 --> 01:24.550
But the chinese government
came up with an audacious scheme

01:24.552 --> 01:27.786
To connect this ancient province
with modern china.

01:27.788 --> 01:35.094
♪

01:35.096 --> 01:38.263
Narrator: This is the highest
railroad on the planet.

01:38.265 --> 01:40.399
♪

01:40.401 --> 01:42.968
Specially-designed,
high-altitude trains

01:42.970 --> 01:47.206
Climb to 16,400 feet
above sea level

01:47.208 --> 01:49.875
To cross the tibetan plateau --

01:49.877 --> 01:54.813
The highest and largest
mountain plateau on earth.

01:54.815 --> 01:56.248
[ speaking native language ]

01:56.250 --> 02:00.219
Interpreter: Our locomotives
can pull 3,700 tons of cargo

02:00.221 --> 02:02.387
Or 20 passenger carriages.

02:02.389 --> 02:05.157
It's the most advanced
technology in our country.

02:07.761 --> 02:10.629
The engineering
is extraordinary.

02:10.631 --> 02:14.466
675 bridges and 10 tunnels

02:14.468 --> 02:16.969
To cross the frozen wilderness

02:16.971 --> 02:20.072
That's known as
"the roof of the world."

02:20.074 --> 02:22.474
[ train horn blows ]

02:22.476 --> 02:25.377
Interpreter:
Whenever I see the train passing
through the tibetan plateau,

02:25.379 --> 02:27.546
I feel extremely proud.

02:27.548 --> 02:30.782
♪

02:30.784 --> 02:33.485
Narrator: From beijing
and shanghai in the east,

02:33.487 --> 02:35.821
Trains run
to the city of golmud,

02:35.823 --> 02:39.091
The start of
the high-altitude line.

02:39.093 --> 02:41.293
From here,
they begin their climb,

02:41.295 --> 02:44.596
Crossing the formerly
impenetrable kunlun mountains

02:44.598 --> 02:48.367
To reach the immense,
frozen tibetan plateau.

02:48.369 --> 02:49.701
At this altitude,

02:49.703 --> 02:52.938
The air oxygen content
is half that at sea level,

02:52.940 --> 02:56.875
And temperatures can drop
below negative 20 degrees.

02:56.877 --> 02:59.711
The railroad reaches
the world's highest station

02:59.713 --> 03:01.647
At the tanggula pass,

03:01.649 --> 03:05.784
A staggering 16,600 feet
above sea level,

03:05.786 --> 03:08.287
Before making its way to lhasa.

03:08.289 --> 03:11.423
♪

03:11.425 --> 03:13.192
[ speaking native language ]

03:13.194 --> 03:15.761
Interpreter:
This is the qinghai-tibet line,

03:15.763 --> 03:19.231
A railway which at first people
thought was impossible.

03:19.233 --> 03:20.432
It's called the heaven road,

03:20.434 --> 03:24.403
And, honestly,
that's what it is.

03:24.405 --> 03:27.306
♪

03:27.308 --> 03:30.976
Narrator:
It's the most audacious
railway project ever imagined,

03:30.978 --> 03:35.180
So it comes with some
enormous challenges.

03:35.182 --> 03:37.182
Perhaps the biggest challenge

03:37.184 --> 03:40.619
Is how do you
keep everyone breathing?

03:40.621 --> 03:42.421
Narrator:
At this incredible altitude,

03:42.423 --> 03:45.057
Oxygen is in short supply.

03:45.059 --> 03:47.292
Dr. Zhu xinxiang is in charge

03:47.294 --> 03:49.394
Of the railway's medical unit.

03:49.396 --> 03:54.967
♪

03:54.969 --> 03:56.468
Interpreter:
On the qinghai-tibet railway

03:56.470 --> 03:58.637
Between golmud and lhasa,

03:58.639 --> 04:02.608
The average altitude
is over 4,000 meters.

04:02.610 --> 04:06.411
It's an area of extremely
low atmospheric pressure.

04:06.413 --> 04:09.514
There's only around 50% oxygen
in the air here

04:09.516 --> 04:12.017
Compared with the mainland.

04:12.019 --> 04:14.186
♪

04:14.188 --> 04:16.355
Narrator: The human body
is not designed to cope

04:16.357 --> 04:18.290
With such low oxygen levels.

04:18.292 --> 04:21.560
It can lead to potentially
fatal altitude sickness.

04:21.562 --> 04:23.662
♪

04:23.664 --> 04:26.665
Interpreter:
In severe cases where
the body's starved of oxygen,

04:26.667 --> 04:29.134
It can cause swelling
of the brain or lungs,

04:29.136 --> 04:31.336
Which can be fatal.

04:31.338 --> 04:33.939
Narrator: These unique trains
are specially engineered

04:33.941 --> 04:35.474
To protect their passengers

04:35.476 --> 04:39.211
As they travel through this
beautiful but brutal landscape.

04:39.213 --> 04:41.847
Ding weiran
is the senior engineer.

04:41.849 --> 04:44.783
[ speaking native language ]

04:44.785 --> 04:46.952
Interpreter:
In here is the oxygen generator,

04:46.954 --> 04:50.088
Which pumps oxygen
into the train carriages.

04:50.090 --> 04:52.958
These prevent oxygen shortages
at high altitude

04:52.960 --> 04:55.460
And make passengers
feel more comfortable.

04:55.462 --> 04:58.263
Inside, there is an altitude
sensor to determine

04:58.265 --> 05:02.167
The oxygen levels outside, and
oxygen concentrations sensors

05:02.169 --> 05:05.804
To monitor the levels
in each passenger compartment.

05:05.806 --> 05:09.007
The train is made up
of 16 carriages,

05:09.009 --> 05:10.342
And each of these carriages

05:10.344 --> 05:13.912
Has its own
oxygen generator like this.

05:17.217 --> 05:20.552
Narrator: The passengers also
have access to oxygen masks,

05:20.554 --> 05:23.055
Which they can use
if they're having difficulties.

05:23.057 --> 05:25.023
Well, if you're just sitting
here, then it's all right,

05:25.025 --> 05:27.225
But if I climb to the top
of the bunk bed,

05:27.227 --> 05:30.762
Then I notice that I have
some shortness of breath.

05:30.764 --> 05:32.297
As an extra precaution,

05:32.299 --> 05:35.667
The railroad posts
a medical team on every train.

05:39.239 --> 05:42.607
These extra measures onboard
ensure safe passage

05:42.609 --> 05:46.478
For the 2 million travelers
who make the journey every year.

05:46.480 --> 05:49.815
But the team that built the line
didn't have these luxuries.

05:49.817 --> 05:51.550
[ speaking native language ]

05:51.552 --> 05:53.719
Interpreter: Construction
workers are at a high risk

05:53.721 --> 05:55.987
Of altitude sickness
and hypoxia --

05:55.989 --> 05:58.824
A severe lack of oxygen.
Doing physical work

05:58.826 --> 06:01.793
Means your body uses up
oxygen very quickly.

06:01.795 --> 06:04.930
That made this an extremely
difficult project.

06:04.932 --> 06:08.433
At first, we thought there was
no way it could be completed.

06:08.435 --> 06:10.435
♪

06:10.437 --> 06:13.205
Narrator: They would need to
turn to a machine from the past

06:13.207 --> 06:17.142
To defy nature and build
across the roof of the world.

06:17.144 --> 06:25.951
♪

06:25.953 --> 06:28.754
Dr. Gary smerdon
is in southwest England

06:28.756 --> 06:31.723
At the site of isambard
brunel's masterpiece,

06:31.725 --> 06:34.626
Discovering how experts
in engineering and medicine

06:34.628 --> 06:37.229
Came together
to solve the problem.

06:37.231 --> 06:39.664
So, here we have
the royal albert bridge,

06:39.666 --> 06:41.767
A fantastic feat of engineering.

06:41.769 --> 06:43.835
Most of the people who travel
across the top of this bridge

06:43.837 --> 06:46.905
Do not have the faintest idea
about the effort

06:46.907 --> 06:49.408
And the suffering that went
into building this bridge,

06:49.410 --> 06:51.843
'cause the feat of engineering
to get that pier built

06:51.845 --> 06:53.712
Down into the rock bed
of the river

06:53.714 --> 06:55.580
Was very new at the time,
very dangerous,

06:55.582 --> 06:58.216
And they didn't really
understand what they were doing.

06:58.218 --> 07:00.218
♪

07:00.220 --> 07:02.754
These workers were moving
into a pressurized environment

07:02.756 --> 07:05.791
Every day to do their digging
and their engineering,

07:05.793 --> 07:08.293
Then coming back to the surface.

07:08.295 --> 07:12.531
There were 25 workers.
One died, two became paraplegic,

07:12.533 --> 07:14.299
And all of the others became ill

07:14.301 --> 07:16.868
Due to what became known
as caisson disease.

07:16.870 --> 07:18.870
♪

07:18.872 --> 07:20.672
Narrator:
With 19th-century engineers

07:20.674 --> 07:23.542
Wanting to build
ever more impressive structures,

07:23.544 --> 07:26.778
A way to treat workers who
came down with caissons disease

07:26.780 --> 07:29.114
Had to be found.

07:29.116 --> 07:32.684
In 1876, american inventor
daniel kelly

07:32.686 --> 07:36.455
Submitted a patent in chicago
for a compressed-air bath,

07:36.457 --> 07:38.123
A machine that would
hold the key

07:38.125 --> 07:40.826
To treating workers
with caissons disease --

07:40.828 --> 07:44.162
Today commonly referred to
as decompression sickness

07:44.164 --> 07:47.299
Or the bends.

07:47.301 --> 07:49.868
The body contains nitrogen gas.

07:49.870 --> 07:51.536
When the pressure increases,

07:51.538 --> 07:54.573
This gas dissolves
into the blood and tissue.

07:54.575 --> 07:56.975
But when the body returns
to normal pressure,

07:56.977 --> 07:59.277
It becomes a gas again.

07:59.279 --> 08:03.014
If bubbles of nitrogen gas form,
they can gather in joints

08:03.016 --> 08:05.951
And tissues,
causing serious problems.

08:05.953 --> 08:08.220
♪

08:08.222 --> 08:10.055
Kelly's machine was a forerunner

08:10.057 --> 08:13.291
Of the hyperbaric chamber.

08:13.293 --> 08:14.593
Any problems,
just put your hand up,

08:14.595 --> 08:15.727
Stay "stop,"
and we'll take it from there.

08:15.729 --> 08:17.963
Lovely.
See you on the surface.

08:17.965 --> 08:20.432
While the condition affecting
the caisson laborers

08:20.434 --> 08:21.733
Was very different

08:21.735 --> 08:24.569
From what the chinese workers
were suffering from,

08:24.571 --> 08:27.072
This amazing machine
holds the key

08:27.074 --> 08:29.774
To solving both problems.

08:29.776 --> 08:32.444
An air compressor
creates pressurized air,

08:32.446 --> 08:34.846
Which is stored in a giant tank.

08:34.848 --> 08:38.984
It's slowly pumped into
the hyperbaric chamber,

08:38.986 --> 08:41.152
Recreating whatever
pressure environment

08:41.154 --> 08:43.922
Doctors need
to treat their patients.

08:43.924 --> 08:47.025
This was the key
to treating caissons disease,

08:47.027 --> 08:49.227
Giving doctors
the ability to reduce

08:49.229 --> 08:51.429
Those deadly bubbles
in the blood.

08:51.431 --> 08:52.864
So, here we are.
We're in the chamber now.

08:52.866 --> 08:54.132
The door is shut.

08:54.134 --> 08:56.334
My colleague, chris,
is at the controls,

08:56.336 --> 08:58.503
And he'll soon be
pressurizing me

08:58.505 --> 09:01.973
And getting me down
to the equivalent of 30 meters.

09:01.975 --> 09:04.309
Narrator: And the machine itself
can actually be used

09:04.311 --> 09:07.479
To demonstrate the very problem
it was built to solve

09:07.481 --> 09:08.980
With a simple experiment.

09:08.982 --> 09:11.650
So, with me here in the chamber,
we have an empty bottle here

09:11.652 --> 09:13.051
That's full of air

09:13.053 --> 09:17.556
And another bottle
that's full of carbonated water.

09:17.558 --> 09:19.257
Narrator:
The empty bottle contains air

09:19.259 --> 09:21.893
At normal sea-level
air pressure.

09:21.895 --> 09:24.162
So as the pressure
in the chamber mounts,

09:24.164 --> 09:25.997
The bottle collapses.

09:25.999 --> 09:27.999
But that's not
the only apparent change

09:28.001 --> 09:29.734
In the pressurized chamber.

09:29.736 --> 09:32.704
[ air hissing ]

09:32.706 --> 09:34.639
Okay, that's you
at 30 meters, gary.

09:34.641 --> 09:36.241
[ high-pitched ]
okay.

09:36.243 --> 09:40.612
Gary's vocal chords
are feeling the pressure, too.

09:40.614 --> 09:42.480
[ high-pitched ]
and there we have a glass

09:42.482 --> 09:45.750
Of carbonated water.

09:45.752 --> 09:48.687
Narrator:
The water, which was carbonated
at normal air pressure,

09:48.689 --> 09:51.389
Has completely lost its fizz.

09:51.391 --> 09:53.959
That much pressure,
the gas molecules

09:53.961 --> 09:57.696
Are dissolved in the liquid,
but the gas is still in there.

09:57.698 --> 10:00.031
Narrator: This water represents
blood in the body.

10:00.033 --> 10:02.567
So when we go back
to the surface, you will see,

10:02.569 --> 10:03.868
Bubbles will start to appear.

10:03.870 --> 10:05.270
That's exactly
what was happening

10:05.272 --> 10:06.671
To these caisson workers,

10:06.673 --> 10:09.174
Where bubbles will start
to appear in your blood

10:09.176 --> 10:12.777
And in your tissues.
As a human, you're in trouble.

10:12.779 --> 10:17.515
♪

10:17.517 --> 10:19.150
Narrator: It was discovered
that the key

10:19.152 --> 10:20.852
To keeping bubbles from forming

10:20.854 --> 10:22.587
Was a slow ascent,

10:22.589 --> 10:25.523
Giving the body time
to equalize.

10:25.525 --> 10:28.727
This machine allowed doctors
to simulate a slower,

10:28.729 --> 10:33.064
Controlled ascent, saving
the lives of caisson workers.

10:33.066 --> 10:35.100
♪

10:35.102 --> 10:38.870
Likewise, the engineers
behind the qinghai-tibet railway

10:38.872 --> 10:40.138
Will take inspiration

10:40.140 --> 10:42.974
From kelly's rudimentary
hyperbaric chamber

10:42.976 --> 10:44.275
To protect the workers

10:44.277 --> 10:47.178
Constructing this
impossible railroad.

11:04.264 --> 11:05.797
Narrator: In china, the team

11:05.799 --> 11:08.133
Building the
qinghai-tibet railway

11:08.135 --> 11:11.336
Realized that daniel kelly's
150-year-old

11:11.338 --> 11:16.141
Air-compressing chamber
could be put to a different use.

11:16.143 --> 11:18.343
[ speaking native language ]

11:18.345 --> 11:21.012
On the 29th of June, 2001,

11:21.014 --> 11:24.149
The build began of the
highest section of the railway.

11:24.151 --> 11:27.352
This was the base hospital
for the construction team.

11:27.354 --> 11:30.755
We provided a lot of
medical personnel and support.

11:30.757 --> 11:34.059
This hyperbaric chamber
was used frequently.

11:36.830 --> 11:40.231
Narrator: The construction team
went through 120,000 bottles

11:40.233 --> 11:44.302
Of oxygen each year,
but even that wasn't enough.

11:44.304 --> 11:46.438
Interpreter: There were many
critically ill patients

11:46.440 --> 11:48.907
During the construction
of the railway.

11:48.909 --> 11:50.608
These chambers were vital.

11:50.610 --> 11:52.877
They saved patients' lives.

11:52.879 --> 11:55.113
♪

11:55.115 --> 11:57.849
Morgan: When you're working
at 4,000 meters altitude,

11:57.851 --> 12:00.452
Getting back down
to sea level isn't easy.

12:00.454 --> 12:03.755
But by placing workers suffering
from altitude sickness

12:03.757 --> 12:07.992
Into hyperbaric chambers,
they could effectively simulate

12:07.994 --> 12:10.328
A move straight back
down to sea level,

12:10.330 --> 12:13.231
Meaning treatment
could start immediately.

12:13.233 --> 12:15.767
Narrator:
Engineers installed 25 chambers

12:15.769 --> 12:19.604
At strategic locations
along the line.

12:19.606 --> 12:21.606
Interpreter: During
the construction of the railway,

12:21.608 --> 12:23.608
The success rate
for saving lives

12:23.610 --> 12:26.945
From acute altitude sickness
was 100%.

12:26.947 --> 12:29.114
There were no fatalities.

12:29.116 --> 12:32.450
♪

12:32.452 --> 12:36.054
This line is a milestone
in the history of railways.

12:36.056 --> 12:38.223
I'm proud of it,
and I'm very proud

12:38.225 --> 12:42.627
Of being part of the medical
team during its construction.

12:42.629 --> 12:45.764
Narrator: This machine helped
keep the 100,000 workers,

12:45.766 --> 12:47.098
Who spent five years

12:47.100 --> 12:50.168
Building this inspirational
railroad, safe.

12:50.170 --> 12:56.975
♪

12:56.977 --> 13:01.079
Mount everest is the
highest mountain in the world,

13:01.081 --> 13:03.448
With the himalayas
making up the southern edge

13:03.450 --> 13:06.451
Of the world's largest
mountain plateau.

13:06.453 --> 13:09.154
Stretching 620 miles north,

13:09.156 --> 13:11.723
The tibetan plateau
is the breathtaking setting

13:11.725 --> 13:14.292
For the highest
railroad on earth.

13:14.294 --> 13:18.263
[ train horn blows ]

13:18.265 --> 13:20.732
In the past, people thought
a railway to lhasa

13:20.734 --> 13:22.100
Could never be done.

13:22.102 --> 13:25.170
It's one of the most
remote cities in the world,

13:25.172 --> 13:27.572
But this didn't stop
the chinese engineers,

13:27.574 --> 13:31.209
And the engineering challenges
they faced were immense.

13:31.211 --> 13:36.881
♪

13:36.883 --> 13:40.151
Narrator: The city of golmud
sits at over 9,000 feet

13:40.153 --> 13:42.687
In the foothills
of the kunlun mountains.

13:42.689 --> 13:44.155
To link it to lhasa,

13:44.157 --> 13:46.925
Engineers needed to find a way
to run rails

13:46.927 --> 13:50.528
Across the permafrost,
permanently frozen ground

13:50.530 --> 13:55.700
Of the 965,000-square-mile
plateau beyond.

13:55.702 --> 13:58.369
Wang jinchang
is professor of engineering

13:58.371 --> 14:00.538
At the railways
research institute

14:00.540 --> 14:03.942
That was tasked
with achieving the impossible.

14:03.944 --> 14:07.545
He regularly makes the 8-hour
round trip from golmud

14:07.547 --> 14:09.080
To the heart of the plateau

14:09.082 --> 14:11.349
To monitor
the ground conditions.

14:11.351 --> 14:13.017
[ speaking native language ]

14:13.019 --> 14:16.287
Interpreter:
The area we're in now is typical
of the tibetan plateau.

14:16.289 --> 14:18.356
It's called "no man's land."

14:18.358 --> 14:21.125
2 or 3 meters beneath us
is permafrost,

14:21.127 --> 14:23.361
Which is permanently
frozen ground.

14:23.363 --> 14:27.065
It's incredibly cold here.

14:27.067 --> 14:30.268
Narrator: Building anything
in this environment isn't easy.

14:30.270 --> 14:31.970
Frozen ground
can actually provide

14:31.972 --> 14:34.172
The perfect foundation
for building on,

14:34.174 --> 14:36.040
But with one
important condition --

14:36.042 --> 14:37.942
It must remain frozen.

14:37.944 --> 14:39.777
If the ground melts
below your foundations,

14:39.779 --> 14:41.312
You're in real trouble.

14:41.314 --> 14:43.381
A railway line
is at risk of collapse,

14:43.383 --> 14:46.217
Derailing any trains
trying to use it.

14:46.219 --> 14:48.686
Narrator: So how do you keep
hundreds of miles of ground

14:48.688 --> 14:51.189
Frozen solid enough to build on?

14:51.191 --> 14:55.293
For inspiration, the engineers
turn to another frozen territory

14:55.295 --> 14:58.196
4,300 miles away.

14:58.198 --> 15:06.838
♪

15:06.840 --> 15:08.840
Known as the last frontier,

15:08.842 --> 15:13.044
Alaska is america's
northernmost state.

15:13.046 --> 15:14.913
Straddling the arctic circle,

15:14.915 --> 15:20.351
It covers a staggering
656,300 square miles.

15:20.353 --> 15:23.955
♪

15:23.957 --> 15:26.190
When the largest oil field
in north america

15:26.192 --> 15:28.359
Was discovered in prudhoe bay,

15:28.361 --> 15:32.764
An 807-mile pipeline down
to the southern port of valdez

15:32.766 --> 15:35.833
Was required to export the oil.

15:35.835 --> 15:39.337
The problem, just like in tibet,
was that they needed to build

15:39.339 --> 15:44.909
On endless expanses of hard
but unstable permafrost.

15:44.911 --> 15:47.145
Local civil engineer
doug goering

15:47.147 --> 15:50.148
Is aware of just how hard
this can be.

15:50.150 --> 15:52.150
Goering: Trying to build any
kind of engineering structure

15:52.152 --> 15:55.753
On this type of permafrost
results in major challenges.

15:55.755 --> 15:57.889
If you try to build a warm
structure like a house

15:57.891 --> 16:00.591
Or a building, you can imagine
that the heat from that building

16:00.593 --> 16:02.627
Is gonna work its way
into the ground.

16:02.629 --> 16:04.896
It thaws the ice
in that ground out,

16:04.898 --> 16:06.931
And it becomes a mushy mess.

16:06.933 --> 16:09.801
The house foundation
typically fails.

16:09.803 --> 16:11.669
Narrator: And when you're trying
to build a pipeline

16:11.671 --> 16:15.974
That will carry warm oil,
those problems are compounded.

16:15.976 --> 16:18.343
Normally, an oil pipeline
would be buried,

16:18.345 --> 16:20.244
But anywhere where
the ground is frozen,

16:20.246 --> 16:23.114
The pipe has to be physically
separated from that frozen soil

16:23.116 --> 16:25.516
Because, of course,
it carries warm oil.

16:25.518 --> 16:27.919
That warm oil would melt
the frozen ground

16:27.921 --> 16:29.354
And cause structural problems --

16:29.356 --> 16:30.955
Cause the pipe
to deform, buckle,

16:30.957 --> 16:35.493
And probably would have
caused oil leaks.

16:35.495 --> 16:37.762
Narrator:
So they built it above ground.

16:37.764 --> 16:40.798
♪

16:40.800 --> 16:44.802
This is
the trans-alaska pipeline...

16:44.804 --> 16:47.071
An $8 billion creation

16:47.073 --> 16:50.141
That carries up to 2 million
barrels of oil a day

16:50.143 --> 16:52.377
Across the entire state.

16:52.379 --> 16:54.379
♪

16:54.381 --> 16:57.181
Goering: The design focused
on an elevated pipeline

16:57.183 --> 17:00.852
To keep the warm pipe
away from that frozen ground.

17:00.854 --> 17:03.087
Narrator: But the foundations
for the support columns

17:03.089 --> 17:06.524
Still needed to rest
on solid, frozen ground.

17:06.526 --> 17:11.996
If it melted, whole sections
of pipeline could collapse.

17:11.998 --> 17:14.699
Luckily, one man had an answer.

17:14.701 --> 17:17.235
♪

17:17.237 --> 17:21.005
In 1963, nuclear physicist
george grover

17:21.007 --> 17:23.141
Developed a system
to transfer heat

17:23.143 --> 17:24.342
That would be crucial

17:24.344 --> 17:28.646
For engineers trying
to build on permafrost.

17:28.648 --> 17:31.349
You can see that each of these
vertical support members

17:31.351 --> 17:34.619
Are capped
by two finned sections.

17:34.621 --> 17:39.690
Those fins sit on top of a
device known as a thermosyphon.

17:39.692 --> 17:43.261
These thermosyphons are used
to ensure that the ground

17:43.263 --> 17:46.998
That the vertical support
members go into remains frozen.

17:47.000 --> 17:48.966
The vertical
support members rely

17:48.968 --> 17:54.472
On that frozen ground strength
to hold the pipe up.

17:54.474 --> 17:57.408
Narrator: A thermosyphon
is essentially an empty tube

17:57.410 --> 18:01.379
Which goes through the marshy
bog down to the frozen ground.

18:01.381 --> 18:03.614
At its base is
a liquid refrigerant

18:03.616 --> 18:05.883
With a low boiling point.

18:05.885 --> 18:08.086
When the temperature rises
in the ground,

18:08.088 --> 18:11.055
The liquid absorbs the heat,
starts to boil,

18:11.057 --> 18:12.723
And then evaporates,

18:12.725 --> 18:15.259
Dissipating the unwanted heat
through the tube

18:15.261 --> 18:16.894
And into the atmosphere,

18:16.896 --> 18:20.198
Keeping the ground around
the foundations cool.

18:20.200 --> 18:22.033
What I have here
is a canister of butane,

18:22.035 --> 18:23.901
Which is similar
to the refrigerant

18:23.903 --> 18:25.603
That's used in the thermosyphon.

18:25.605 --> 18:27.738
And what I'm gonna do here
for a demonstration

18:27.740 --> 18:31.576
Is get a little bit of liquid
butane into this plastic bag.

18:35.715 --> 18:38.416
So you can see that I have
liquid in the bag, here.

18:38.418 --> 18:40.251
What happens at the base
of the thermosyphon

18:40.253 --> 18:41.452
Is that liquid boils.

18:41.454 --> 18:43.387
And you can see that
when I add heat

18:43.389 --> 18:47.058
By putting my fingers
on this bag,

18:47.060 --> 18:49.360
That I get pretty vigorous
boiling of the butane.

18:49.362 --> 18:51.329
This is the same thing
that's happening

18:51.331 --> 18:53.264
At the base of the thermosyphon.

18:53.266 --> 18:56.968
In this case, the butane is
collecting heat from my fingers.

18:56.970 --> 18:58.803
In the case
of the thermosyphons,

18:58.805 --> 19:01.339
The refrigerant collects heat
from the permafrost

19:01.341 --> 19:03.207
And pulls heat out of it --

19:03.209 --> 19:05.743
Dumps that heat
into the atmosphere.

19:05.745 --> 19:09.247
♪

19:09.249 --> 19:11.649
Narrator:
Over 100,000 thermosyphons

19:11.651 --> 19:14.385
Help to keep the oil flowing.

19:14.387 --> 19:17.054
Goering: This pipeline project
really is an engineering marvel.

19:17.056 --> 19:19.624
It's been stable for
on the order of 40 years.

19:19.626 --> 19:21.626
Really, I think it's safe to say
that the engineers

19:21.628 --> 19:24.595
Who designed this
solved the permafrost challenge.

19:24.597 --> 19:29.934
♪

19:29.936 --> 19:35.273
♪

19:35.275 --> 19:37.875
The permafrost challenge
has not beaten the team

19:37.877 --> 19:39.477
In tibet, either.

19:39.479 --> 19:42.947
Here, they've used thermosyphons
on a massive scale,

19:42.949 --> 19:45.483
Stretching as far
as the eye can see

19:45.485 --> 19:49.587
To cross over 310 miles
of permafrost.

19:49.589 --> 19:52.256
[ speaking native language ]

19:52.258 --> 19:55.560
Interpreter:
These thermosyphons are the
best way to solve the problem.

19:55.562 --> 19:57.361
It's a great solution.

19:57.363 --> 20:00.431
Its main function is to decrease
the temperature of the ground

20:00.433 --> 20:02.733
And prevent the permafrost
from melting.

20:02.735 --> 20:05.770
This is the part
that releases heat.

20:05.772 --> 20:07.171
This is the middle section,

20:07.173 --> 20:09.373
And the working part
is underground.

20:09.375 --> 20:12.710
We use two rows of thermosyphons
on the side facing the sun

20:12.712 --> 20:15.546
And one row on the side
which doesn't face the sun.

20:15.548 --> 20:17.648
♪

20:17.650 --> 20:22.286
Narrator:
Over 25,000 thermosyphons
have been installed.

20:22.288 --> 20:25.122
But with the heat generated
from passing trains,

20:25.124 --> 20:28.859
The thermosyphons alone aren't
enough to keep the ground frozen

20:28.861 --> 20:31.095
And the foundation solid.

20:31.097 --> 20:33.564
The track is also raised
off the ground

20:33.566 --> 20:37.435
On a crushed rock embankment.

20:37.437 --> 20:40.638
This low-tech engineering works
by letting the cold wind

20:40.640 --> 20:43.207
Flow through the gaps
between the rocks,

20:43.209 --> 20:46.544
Dissipating any heat
coming from the trains above.

20:46.546 --> 20:48.412
[ speaking native language ]

20:48.414 --> 20:50.648
Interpreter: By using these
measures, we protect the railway

20:50.650 --> 20:54.585
By keeping the ground cool up to
15 meters away from the track.

20:54.587 --> 20:56.387
This prevents the permafrost
from melting

20:56.389 --> 20:58.489
And sinking the railway.

20:58.491 --> 21:01.926
♪

21:01.928 --> 21:05.830
Narrator:
But for a 7.3-mile long stretch
of the permafrost zone

21:05.832 --> 21:07.498
In the heart of the plateau,

21:07.500 --> 21:09.967
Neither of these measures
could help.

21:09.969 --> 21:13.070
To make this unbuildable
stretch buildable,

21:13.072 --> 21:17.041
Engineers would need
to make the impossible possible.

21:34.894 --> 21:36.727
[ speaking native language ]

21:36.729 --> 21:40.631
Interpreter:
We're now at the chumaer river
upland plain natural reserve.

21:40.633 --> 21:42.266
This is all wetlands.

21:42.268 --> 21:45.403
The biggest feature here
is the hydrothermal lakes.

21:45.405 --> 21:48.105
This is a natural occurrence
of frozen soil.

21:50.943 --> 21:54.111
Narrator: While in the winter
this area is frozen solid,

21:54.113 --> 21:56.013
The heat from
the hydrothermal lakes

21:56.015 --> 21:59.383
Means it's all a boggy marshland
come summer.

21:59.385 --> 22:01.819
♪

22:01.821 --> 22:04.555
So this is the
incredible solution.

22:04.557 --> 22:06.991
♪

22:06.993 --> 22:08.726
At over 6.8 miles,

22:08.728 --> 22:12.463
It's the longest bridge
over permafrost in the world.

22:12.465 --> 22:14.665
♪

22:14.667 --> 22:17.201
Interpreter: Most of
the frozen soil is melted here.

22:17.203 --> 22:20.504
A rock embankment wouldn't be
stable, so we built a bridge.

22:20.506 --> 22:22.740
The bridge is supported
by pile foundations,

22:22.742 --> 22:25.042
Which were inserted
deeply into the ground.

22:25.044 --> 22:27.678
In this environment, a bridge
is a much better solution

22:27.680 --> 22:29.447
Than an embankment.

22:29.449 --> 22:33.017
♪

22:33.019 --> 22:35.786
The biggest difficulty for us
building this kind of bridge

22:35.788 --> 22:37.421
Is working in winter.

22:37.423 --> 22:40.925
During summer, the atmospheric
temperature is too high.

22:40.927 --> 22:43.094
If we built during this season,
we would risk

22:43.096 --> 22:47.531
Causing the permafrost to melt,
making it too unstable.

22:47.533 --> 22:50.668
♪

22:50.670 --> 22:52.036
Narrator:
Working through winter

22:52.038 --> 22:55.139
At temperatures
down to minus-22 degrees,

22:55.141 --> 22:57.241
Engineers achieved
the impossible

22:57.243 --> 22:59.777
And completed the final,
most difficult part

22:59.779 --> 23:02.113
Of the line to lhasa.

23:02.115 --> 23:04.081
[ speaking native language ]
interpreter: Building a railway

23:04.083 --> 23:06.517
In the permafrost
of the tibetan plateau

23:06.519 --> 23:08.652
Was one of the biggest
engineering challenges

23:08.654 --> 23:10.521
In the world.

23:10.523 --> 23:13.924
♪

23:13.926 --> 23:17.228
Morgan: It was almost impossible
to conceive of a railway

23:17.230 --> 23:19.130
Running at this altitude.

23:19.132 --> 23:23.401
It's an extraordinary feat
of human ingenuity.

23:23.403 --> 23:25.503
♪

23:25.505 --> 23:28.472
Narrator: To construct
this $5.2 billion line

23:28.474 --> 23:30.274
To run at high altitude,

23:30.276 --> 23:32.743
Engineers overcame huge hurdles,

23:32.745 --> 23:36.614
But they also had to specially
engineer the locomotive itself.

23:36.616 --> 23:41.352
♪

23:41.354 --> 23:44.121
Across most of the china
railway network,

23:44.123 --> 23:45.890
Electric locomotives are used,

23:45.892 --> 23:49.994
Which draw their power
from overhead cables.

23:49.996 --> 23:52.763
The shanghai to lhasa express
uses these

23:52.765 --> 23:55.065
For the first part
of the 47-hour,

23:55.067 --> 23:59.703
2.6-thousand-mile journey
across the country.

23:59.705 --> 24:03.541
But when the train reaches
golmud, it runs into trouble.

24:03.543 --> 24:05.776
♪

24:05.778 --> 24:07.978
Morgan: In the isolated,
high-altitude plateau,

24:07.980 --> 24:09.814
Extremely low
winter temperatures

24:09.816 --> 24:11.682
Combined with lightning storms

24:11.684 --> 24:15.820
Means that electricity supply
cannot be guaranteed.

24:15.822 --> 24:18.722
So they can't install
the overhead cables

24:18.724 --> 24:21.258
Necessary to electric trains.

24:21.260 --> 24:23.294
♪

24:23.296 --> 24:25.062
Narrator:
Normally, railroad engineers

24:25.064 --> 24:27.832
Would turn to
a regular diesel locomotive.

24:27.834 --> 24:31.469
Morgan: Combustion engines need
fuel and oxygen to work,

24:31.471 --> 24:34.805
But at these altitudes,
there's just not enough oxygen

24:34.807 --> 24:37.208
To give enough power
to the engines

24:37.210 --> 24:42.112
To haul the huge trains
up the steep gradients required.

24:42.114 --> 24:44.348
Narrator: Internal combustion
engines draw air

24:44.350 --> 24:47.084
Into the combustion chamber
to mix with fuel.

24:47.086 --> 24:50.754
The piston compresses it.
Then the spark plug ignites it.

24:50.756 --> 24:52.156
This controlled explosion

24:52.158 --> 24:54.859
Forces the piston
back down the cylinder.

24:54.861 --> 24:56.660
But as oxygen levels drop,

24:56.662 --> 24:58.596
So does the force
of the explosion

24:58.598 --> 25:00.364
And the power produced.

25:00.366 --> 25:02.966
Regular locomotives just
wouldn't be able to cope

25:02.968 --> 25:04.235
With the lack of oxygen.

25:04.237 --> 25:07.037
They wouldn't get
anywhere near lhasa.

25:07.039 --> 25:09.874
Narrator: To get trains to run
at such high altitudes,

25:09.876 --> 25:12.776
The engineers needed
to look to the skies.

25:12.778 --> 25:18.415
♪

25:18.417 --> 25:24.054
♪

25:24.056 --> 25:27.825
Mechanical engineer dan dickrell
is exploring pikes peak,

25:27.827 --> 25:31.962
One of the highest points
in the rocky mountains.

25:31.964 --> 25:35.866
It was here in 1918
that a landmark experiment

25:35.868 --> 25:39.203
Changed engine design forever.

25:39.205 --> 25:41.205
Dickrell:
Driving this really muscley car

25:41.207 --> 25:44.074
Up one of america's
most iconic highways

25:44.076 --> 25:46.343
Is quite exciting
from both an engineering

25:46.345 --> 25:49.446
And an auto-enthusiast
perspective.

25:49.448 --> 25:51.115
Narrator:
But as the road climbs,

25:51.117 --> 25:55.653
The amount of oxygen
in the air falls.

25:55.655 --> 25:59.123
Dickrell: I've reached
the halfway point up pikes peak.

25:59.125 --> 26:03.260
I can feel that lack of oxygen
at this altitude,

26:03.262 --> 26:05.696
And so the automobile.

26:05.698 --> 26:06.964
At the bottom,
it was really snappy.

26:06.966 --> 26:09.233
It's starting to get
a little bit more sluggish.

26:09.235 --> 26:12.703
Narrator:
At the 14,115-foot summit,

26:12.705 --> 26:16.206
The oxygen is almost 50% lower
than at sea level.

26:16.208 --> 26:18.742
All right.

26:18.744 --> 26:20.377
I can really, really feel it.

26:20.379 --> 26:23.280
Lightheaded. Do not feel great.

26:23.282 --> 26:24.782
And on the way up,

26:24.784 --> 26:27.851
The internal combustion engine
inside my car,

26:27.853 --> 26:29.486
It could feel it, too.

26:29.488 --> 26:32.256
♪

26:32.258 --> 26:34.959
Narrator: This problem plagued
early aircraft pioneers,

26:34.961 --> 26:37.494
Who found the higher
they took their machines,

26:37.496 --> 26:41.265
The more their engine's
power faded.

26:41.267 --> 26:44.435
And during world war I,
the ability to fly high

26:44.437 --> 26:47.705
Became a matter
of life and death.

26:47.707 --> 26:49.473
The higher a plane could get,

26:49.475 --> 26:53.077
The smaller the chance of
it being detected by the enemy.

26:53.079 --> 26:55.212
They had to find a way
for their engines

26:55.214 --> 26:57.348
To cope with lower oxygen levels

26:57.350 --> 27:00.684
So they could go higher
than ever before.

27:00.686 --> 27:02.553
And the solution they landed on

27:02.555 --> 27:06.056
Just might hold the answers
for the team in china.

27:22.208 --> 27:25.676
Narrator:
For a solution to their
low-oxygen, high-power needs,

27:25.678 --> 27:28.779
The engineers behind
the qinghai-tibet railway

27:28.781 --> 27:32.349
Must turn to an innovator
of the past.

27:32.351 --> 27:33.851
During world war ii,

27:33.853 --> 27:36.987
Aircraft designers
needed to maintain engine power

27:36.989 --> 27:41.892
At increasingly high altitudes
to avoid radar detection.

27:41.894 --> 27:45.095
To help the u.S. Air force
solve their lofty problem,

27:45.097 --> 27:50.034
They drafted in steam turbine
engineer sanford moss.

27:50.036 --> 27:53.303
Dickrell:
Sanford moss developed a
revolutionary piece of machinery

27:53.305 --> 27:56.206
That would force more air
into the airplane engine,

27:56.208 --> 27:59.710
Essentially turbo-charging it.

27:59.712 --> 28:03.914
Narrator: Moss' turbocharger
was a total game changer.

28:03.916 --> 28:07.284
Instead of just being wasted,
the engine's exhaust gas

28:07.286 --> 28:09.853
Is used to spin a turbine,

28:09.855 --> 28:11.655
Which in turn powers
a compressor,

28:11.657 --> 28:15.192
Which draws in air,
compresses it, cools it,

28:15.194 --> 28:18.295
And pushes it into
the combustion chamber.

28:18.297 --> 28:20.798
This high-pressure mix,
when ignited,

28:20.800 --> 28:24.201
Dramatically increases
the engine's power.

28:24.203 --> 28:26.170
To demonstrate
the difference it makes,

28:26.172 --> 28:30.474
First we need to see how
an engine performs without it.

28:30.476 --> 28:32.142
This is gonna serve
as my cylinder.

28:32.144 --> 28:35.646
Inside the cylinder, we're gonna
put a mixture of fuel and air.

28:35.648 --> 28:37.214
Instead of gasoline,

28:37.216 --> 28:41.251
I'm gonna use butane.

28:41.253 --> 28:45.022
Now, what I'm gonna do is
I'm gonna take this butane...

28:45.024 --> 28:49.393
And inject it into
my cylinder...

28:49.395 --> 28:54.631
And two metal electrodes
are gonna serve as a spark plug.

28:54.633 --> 28:57.868
I'm gonna introduce
two alligator clips

28:57.870 --> 29:01.105
That will provide electricity.

29:01.107 --> 29:03.874
♪

29:03.876 --> 29:08.679
In three, two, one.

29:08.681 --> 29:11.148
Cool.

29:11.150 --> 29:13.484
All right, now we're gonna
repeat the same demonstration,

29:13.486 --> 29:17.721
Except this time, I'm gonna
turbo-charge the cylinder.

29:17.723 --> 29:21.158
To do that,
still need some fuel.

29:21.160 --> 29:23.827
Now, this time,
we're gonna introduce

29:23.829 --> 29:25.329
A slightly different cork,

29:25.331 --> 29:27.798
'cause this one
as a valve in it.

29:27.800 --> 29:32.636
That's gonna allow me
to pressurize the cylinder,

29:32.638 --> 29:35.272
Just like a turbocharger would.

29:35.274 --> 29:37.674
We lock down...

29:37.676 --> 29:40.878
Give it a few good pumps...

29:40.880 --> 29:43.380
And now I've got
my pressurized cylinder.

29:43.382 --> 29:45.516
Let's repeat

29:45.518 --> 29:48.418
And see what the effect
has on it.

29:48.420 --> 29:52.055
In three, two, one, go!

29:52.057 --> 29:53.791
[ chuckling ] whoa! Nice!

29:53.793 --> 29:56.460
Oh, that one flew
much, much higher.

29:56.462 --> 29:58.996
The turbocharged cylinder
worked much better

29:58.998 --> 30:02.833
In terms of explosive
release of energy,

30:02.835 --> 30:05.235
Just like a turbocharged
engine would.

30:05.237 --> 30:08.372
♪

30:08.374 --> 30:11.575
Narrator: In 1918,
moss and his team came here

30:11.577 --> 30:14.878
To carry out their first
high-altitude test.

30:14.880 --> 30:16.880
♪

30:16.882 --> 30:20.250
He put his new turbocharged
engine on the back of a truck

30:20.252 --> 30:24.521
And attached it
to a giant propeller.

30:24.523 --> 30:28.358
The output had been
230 horsepower.

30:28.360 --> 30:29.860
But with his new invention,

30:29.862 --> 30:33.363
It was boosted
to 356 horsepower.

30:33.365 --> 30:38.535
♪

30:38.537 --> 30:41.205
Dickrell: Three years
afterwards, a biplane fitted

30:41.207 --> 30:44.107
With a moss device
broke the altitude record,

30:44.109 --> 30:47.911
Flying higher than any other
airplane had flown before.

30:47.913 --> 30:51.281
Turbochargers exist
all over the place.

30:51.283 --> 30:53.617
Really impressive pieces
of technology.

30:53.619 --> 30:59.356
♪

30:59.358 --> 31:05.195
♪

31:05.197 --> 31:08.432
Narrator: In china, engineers
have fitted moss' turbocharger

31:08.434 --> 31:11.368
To special locomotives
to give them the power

31:11.370 --> 31:15.706
To cross the high-altitude
tibetan plateau.

31:15.708 --> 31:19.409
At golmud station,
locomotive engineer shen dezhi

31:19.411 --> 31:22.546
Is supervising the switch-over.

31:22.548 --> 31:25.215
[ speaking native language ]

31:25.217 --> 31:28.018
Interpreter:
This train has just arrived
from beijing to the east.

31:28.020 --> 31:29.586
It's an electric locomotive,

31:29.588 --> 31:32.990
Powered from
the overhead cables.

31:32.992 --> 31:35.359
After the crew have
disconnected all the wires,

31:35.361 --> 31:39.429
It will be pulled out so that
the new locomotive can come in.

31:39.431 --> 31:42.633
♪

31:42.635 --> 31:44.534
Narrator: With the passengers
eager to continue

31:44.536 --> 31:47.804
The next 14-hour leg
of their journey to lhasa,

31:47.806 --> 31:50.307
The train crew
must move quickly.

31:50.309 --> 31:52.976
[ speaking native language ]

31:52.978 --> 31:56.346
Interpreter:
This is our solution
to the high-altitude problem.

31:56.348 --> 31:59.016
It's a tailor-made
plateau diesel locomotive,

31:59.018 --> 32:02.753
Especially designed
for the qinghai-tibet line.

32:02.755 --> 32:06.490
It's about to be connected
to these carriages.

32:06.492 --> 32:14.698
♪

32:14.700 --> 32:18.335
Narrator: These turbo diesel
engines provide 6,000 horsepower

32:18.337 --> 32:20.871
To pull either
20 passenger carriages

32:20.873 --> 32:23.941
Or a whopping 3,700
tons of freight

32:23.943 --> 32:27.377
At speeds of up
to 75 miles an hour.

32:27.379 --> 32:30.614
♪

32:30.616 --> 32:33.016
[ speaking native language ]

32:33.018 --> 32:35.052
Interpreter: I had the honor
of driving the first train

32:35.054 --> 32:37.220
To cross the plateau to lhasa.

32:37.222 --> 32:39.623
So whenever I see this
incredible, advanced locomotive

32:39.625 --> 32:43.393
Coming into golmud,
I feel excited, very excited.

32:43.395 --> 32:48.732
♪

32:48.734 --> 32:51.735
If we don't manage to build
this turbocharged locomotive,

32:51.737 --> 32:54.871
So many people just wouldn't
be able to get to lhasa.

32:54.873 --> 32:58.275
I feel very proud
of this solution.

32:58.277 --> 33:04.614
♪

33:04.616 --> 33:08.352
Narrator: But the engineers
still face another major hurdle.

33:08.354 --> 33:09.886
The single-line design

33:09.888 --> 33:12.990
Makes reliable
communications essential.

33:12.992 --> 33:15.325
With high-speed trains traveling
in opposite directions

33:15.327 --> 33:18.462
In some of the most
remote locations on earth,

33:18.464 --> 33:20.397
How do you ensure you can
communicate with them

33:20.399 --> 33:21.965
To keep them safe?

33:34.213 --> 33:42.986
♪

33:42.988 --> 33:44.921
Narrator: The highest
railroad in the world

33:44.923 --> 33:47.190
Runs to lhasa station.

33:47.192 --> 33:51.261
♪

33:51.263 --> 33:53.764
Trains on this line
are specially engineered

33:53.766 --> 33:58.201
To cross the frozen tundra
of the tibetan plateau.

33:58.203 --> 34:02.973
Undercarriages are sealed
to protect against frost damage,

34:02.975 --> 34:05.342
And even the windows
are specially designed

34:05.344 --> 34:07.778
To cope with subzero
temperatures.

34:09.982 --> 34:12.949
Interpreter:
The windows are equipped
with a special heating device.

34:12.951 --> 34:15.118
It prevents the glass
from freezing and cracking

34:15.120 --> 34:16.953
As the train travels
along the cold parts

34:16.955 --> 34:20.857
Of the golmud to lhasa line.

34:20.859 --> 34:22.659
Narrator:
These incredible advances

34:22.661 --> 34:25.929
Make this previously impossible
journey possible

34:25.931 --> 34:30.367
For passengers like gregor and
marianne, tourists from holland.

34:30.369 --> 34:32.536
Messelink:
Yeah, it's definitely amazing.

34:32.538 --> 34:34.171
I'm reading a book right now

34:34.173 --> 34:37.340
About a woman
who's traveling in tibet

34:37.342 --> 34:39.543
I think about 20 years ago,

34:39.545 --> 34:40.877
And it was so different.

34:40.879 --> 34:43.280
You had to do everything by foot
or with a jeep.

34:43.282 --> 34:44.681
And if there were
mud floods,

34:44.683 --> 34:46.516
Then you couldn't go
any further.

34:46.518 --> 34:48.151
It's really
a totally different setting

34:48.153 --> 34:53.190
To just cruise through
the mountains in warm trains.

34:53.192 --> 34:55.892
♪

34:55.894 --> 34:58.962
Narrator: The 710 miles
of high-altitude railroad

34:58.964 --> 35:00.897
Between golmud and lhasa

35:00.899 --> 35:04.634
Includes a staggering
675 bridges

35:04.636 --> 35:08.171
And almost 6 miles of tunnels,

35:08.173 --> 35:12.576
Including the highest
railroad tunnel in the world --

35:12.578 --> 35:16.246
The 4,400-foot-long
fenghuoshan tunnel,

35:16.248 --> 35:19.049
Drilled through
a permanently frozen mountain.

35:19.051 --> 35:23.620
♪

35:23.622 --> 35:27.324
Morgan:
Building this line really pushed
the boundaries of engineering.

35:27.326 --> 35:30.026
But with a £3 billion price tag,

35:30.028 --> 35:33.830
They simply couldn't afford
to build two lines side-by-side,

35:33.832 --> 35:35.332
One for each direction,

35:35.334 --> 35:38.668
So they had to settle
for a single line.

35:38.670 --> 35:41.138
This presented engineers
with a new challenge.

35:41.140 --> 35:43.440
With high-speed trains traveling
in opposite directions

35:43.442 --> 35:46.576
In some of the most
remote locations on earth,

35:46.578 --> 35:48.512
How do you ensure
you can communicate with them

35:48.514 --> 35:51.781
To keep them safe?

35:51.783 --> 35:55.886
Narrator:
So how could an innovation from
19th-century railroad pioneers

35:55.888 --> 35:58.755
Help inspire
the engineers in china?

35:58.757 --> 36:04.161
♪

36:04.163 --> 36:09.466
♪

36:09.468 --> 36:12.903
Engineer kate mulcahy
is at miniatur wunderland

36:12.905 --> 36:15.672
In the german city of hamburg --

36:15.674 --> 36:19.442
The largest model railroad
in the world.

36:19.444 --> 36:23.013
1,300 trains
with over 10,000 carriages

36:23.015 --> 36:25.182
Crisscross this huge attraction,

36:25.184 --> 36:26.950
Where they have
a similar problem --

36:26.952 --> 36:28.885
Keeping trains safe.

36:28.887 --> 36:35.358
♪

36:35.360 --> 36:38.595
Luckily, an ingenious,
new form of technology

36:38.597 --> 36:41.831
Was about to change
the way the world communicated,

36:41.833 --> 36:45.602
Setting in motion
a telecommunications revolution.

36:47.873 --> 36:51.074
Narrator: In 1837,
william fothergill cooke

36:51.076 --> 36:54.744
And charles wheatstone struck
upon a brilliant concept --

36:54.746 --> 36:57.080
Electromagnetic deflection.

36:57.082 --> 36:59.916
They found that when they
created a complete circuit,

36:59.918 --> 37:02.652
Magnets reacted
to each other predictably,

37:02.654 --> 37:05.055
Even across great distances.

37:05.057 --> 37:07.524
♪

37:07.526 --> 37:10.260
Cooke and wheatstone
built this instrument --

37:10.262 --> 37:13.763
The five-needle telegraph
arranged on a grid of letters.

37:13.765 --> 37:16.166
Now, in my version,
my construction here,

37:16.168 --> 37:19.035
This bit represents
the sending element,

37:19.037 --> 37:20.904
And then this bit over here

37:20.906 --> 37:23.240
Represents
the receiving element.

37:23.242 --> 37:26.943
These rods in the middle
represent wires.

37:26.945 --> 37:29.879
Now, because this telegraph,
the sending one,

37:29.881 --> 37:33.283
Is connected in the circuit
to this telegraph,

37:33.285 --> 37:36.186
When I move this needle one way,

37:36.188 --> 37:39.689
The action is mirrored in the
receiving telegraph over here.

37:39.691 --> 37:42.058
So, for example,
if I wanted to spell out,

37:42.060 --> 37:45.428
Say, the word "stop,"
I start with the letter "s."

37:45.430 --> 37:47.864
So, on my sending,

37:47.866 --> 37:51.668
I'll move this needle so it
points towards "s,"

37:51.670 --> 37:56.339
And I'll move this needle
so it points towards "s,"

37:56.341 --> 37:58.141
And then the person
on the receiving end

37:58.143 --> 38:01.344
Will look for where the points
of those needles converge.

38:01.346 --> 38:04.214
I then need to move the needles

38:04.216 --> 38:09.085
So that I can get them
to converge on "t."

38:09.087 --> 38:12.289
Narrator: This device enabled
its users to spell out words

38:12.291 --> 38:15.859
And send them down the wire.

38:15.861 --> 38:17.694
Their feat
of engineering brilliance

38:17.696 --> 38:20.330
Was to send the first
communication

38:20.332 --> 38:24.634
Electronically on the railways.

38:24.636 --> 38:29.506
Narrator:
The needle telegraph started
a telecommunications revolution.

38:29.508 --> 38:31.775
Adopted by the rail
network initially,

38:31.777 --> 38:34.477
It was quickly
implemented worldwide.

38:34.479 --> 38:42.686
♪

38:42.688 --> 38:47.057
In china, they've taken
this 180-year-old concept

38:47.059 --> 38:50.493
And given it
a 21st-century makeover.

39:07.646 --> 39:10.714
Narrator: Third-generation
railway man wang jinchang

39:10.716 --> 39:14.217
Manages the golmud
train station,

39:14.219 --> 39:16.753
And the technology he uses
to signal trains

39:16.755 --> 39:19.856
On the qinghai-tibet railway
is a far cry

39:19.858 --> 39:24.561
From the 19th-century innovation
that inspired it.

39:24.563 --> 39:27.230
[ speaking native language ]

39:27.232 --> 39:28.765
Interpreter:
Between golmud and lhasa,

39:28.767 --> 39:31.267
We use satellite
positioning signals.

39:31.269 --> 39:35.238
You won't see a single trackside
signal on the golmud-lhasa line.

39:35.240 --> 39:36.973
[ speaking native language ]

39:36.975 --> 39:38.775
Interpreter: We use the
satellite positioning signals

39:38.777 --> 39:40.510
Due to the tough
weather conditions

39:40.512 --> 39:43.179
And 4,000-meter-high altitude.

39:43.181 --> 39:45.382
This is a great piece
of technology.

39:45.384 --> 39:47.550
It's a massive leap forward.

39:49.621 --> 39:51.454
Narrator:
The train control system is run

39:51.456 --> 39:55.358
From a control room
at xining station.

39:55.360 --> 39:57.127
With global
positioning satellites

39:57.129 --> 39:59.729
Determining the train locations,

39:59.731 --> 40:02.966
All signaling is virtual
instead of wayside signals

40:02.968 --> 40:05.268
Used by cooke
and wheatstone's system.

40:05.270 --> 40:08.938
All information is communicated
directly into the train cab,

40:08.940 --> 40:10.607
Where an onboard
computer terminal

40:10.609 --> 40:14.210
Displays up-to-the-second
information to the driver.

40:14.212 --> 40:17.213
♪

40:17.215 --> 40:20.383
[ speaking native language ]

40:20.385 --> 40:23.086
Interpreter:
The advanced technologies
implemented along this line

40:23.088 --> 40:26.389
Are unique in this country.

40:26.391 --> 40:28.792
They are the only reason
that we can provide tibet

40:28.794 --> 40:31.461
With the heaven road railway
that's been so important

40:31.463 --> 40:34.264
For their economic growth
and social development.

40:36.802 --> 40:39.736
Narrator: The golmud-to-lhasa
line has transformed travel

40:39.738 --> 40:42.105
Across the tibetan plateau.

40:42.107 --> 40:44.374
[ laughter, indistinct
conversations ]

40:44.376 --> 40:45.875
[ speaking native language ]

40:45.877 --> 40:47.143
Interpreter:
Business increased quickly

40:47.145 --> 40:49.646
Once the golmud-to-lhasa
line opened.

40:49.648 --> 40:50.747
Just in the last year,

40:50.749 --> 40:53.149
We've dispatched
over a million passengers,

40:53.151 --> 40:55.385
And the goods we have
transported by rail

40:55.387 --> 40:58.721
Have sharply reduced the number
of lorries on the road.

40:58.723 --> 41:00.824
Lifestyle products,
building materials,

41:00.826 --> 41:02.826
And daily necessities
such as oil

41:02.828 --> 41:07.897
Are basically all
transported by rail now.

41:07.899 --> 41:15.138
♪

41:15.140 --> 41:22.378
♪

41:22.380 --> 41:25.415
Narrator:
Building a railroad line
across the roof of the world

41:25.417 --> 41:27.784
Was never going to be easy.

41:27.786 --> 41:32.121
♪

41:32.123 --> 41:33.823
Interpreter: When we were young,
we didn't think

41:33.825 --> 41:36.926
There would ever be a railway
between golmud and lhasa.

41:36.928 --> 41:42.232
I think it's a milestone in
the history of global railway.

41:42.234 --> 41:44.901
Narrator: The unprecedented
and ambitious project

41:44.903 --> 41:47.837
Stands as testament
to the tenacious perseverance

41:47.839 --> 41:50.039
Of the human spirit.

41:50.041 --> 41:51.374
[ speaking native language ]

41:51.376 --> 41:53.643
Interpreter: If this special
locomotive didn't exist,

41:53.645 --> 41:56.813
So many passengers wouldn't
be able to get to lhasa,

41:56.815 --> 42:00.083
So I feel very proud
of this train.

42:00.085 --> 42:03.019
Dickrell: Go!
[ chuckling ] whoa! Nice!

42:03.021 --> 42:04.454
Narrator:
By building on the work

42:04.456 --> 42:09.526
Of the inspirational pioneers
of the past, upscaling,

42:09.528 --> 42:12.862
And breaking
new ground themselves,

42:12.864 --> 42:14.731
The engineers have succeeded

42:14.733 --> 42:19.035
In making
the impossible possible.

42:19.037 --> 42:22.171
Narrator:
The qinghai-tibet railway is the
greatest engineering achievement

42:22.173 --> 42:23.873
In the world.
